result.execSummary:
The defendant Kaleb L Seitz was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Resisting/Obstructing. This is not a criminal offense and results only in a money penalty for this offense.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
9:21 AM Defendant Kaleb L Seitz appeared by video from Winnebago Mental Health Institution.  Attorney Eryn M Menden in court for Kaleb L Seitz. District Attorney's Office Law Intern appeared for the State of Wisconsin by Abigail Kincheloe. 

Defense believes case is resolved. 

Prosecuting attorney moves to amend to Resisting/Obstructing contrary to section 13.102(c)(7) of the Waukesha County Code of Ordinances.  Court approves amendment.  No contest plea entered.  Court finds the defendant guilty.

Court orders the following:
FINE: $267.50. Court will apply 12 days of jail credit at $100.00/day.

Defendant to have no contact with the co-actor listed in the Criminal Complaint.  Defendant is not to share, reproduce or distribute any personal and/or identifying information about the crime victim(s), except to their attorney.

1:43 PM Defendant Kaleb L Seitz in court, in custody.  Attorney Eryn M Menden in court for Kaleb L Seitz. District Attorney's Office Law Intern appeared for the State of Wisconsin by Julian Marrufo.  The Court goes over the procedural history of the case.  The State gives its bail recommendation.  The Defense gives its bail recommendation.  The Court quashes the warrant.
Hearing scheduled for September 12, 2022 at 09:00 am.

The Court will adjourn the matter to tomorrow.
